"Efremova T.T., Efremov S.P., Melent'eva N.V.","Nitrogen in Russian Bogs",2000,"Eurasian Soil Science","33","9",,"934","946",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0042690965&partnerID=40&md5=594ffde9144cc91930b80cdf4a11a445","Sukachev Institute of Forestry, Siberian Division, Russian Academy of Sciences, Akademgorodok, Krasnoyarsk, 660036, Russian Federation","Efremova, T.T., Sukachev Institute of Forestry, Siberian Division, Russian Academy of Sciences, Akademgorodok, Krasnoyarsk, 660036, Russian Federation; Efremov, S.P., Sukachev Institute of Forestry, Siberian Division, Russian Academy of Sciences, Akademgorodok, Krasnoyarsk, 660036, Russian Federation; Melent'eva, N.V., Sukachev Institute of Forestry, Siberian Division, Russian Academy of Sciences, Akademgorodok, Krasnoyarsk, 660036, Russian Federation","The nitrogen pool in Russian peatlands reaches 4.69 × 109 t. Half of this amount is stored in humic substances (mainly, in humic acids) of peat. The nitrogen of relatively stable compounds (mainly, the humin nitrogen) constitutes about 1.8 × 109 t. Easily hydrolyzable and mineral nitrogen compounds constitute 9.7 and 1.8% of the total nitrogen pool, respectively. Most of the nitrogen in eutrophic bogs is bound with humic substances, while that of oligotrophic peat is represented by poorly hydrolyzable and nonhydrolyzable forms. The pool of water-soluble nitrogen constitutes 20.3 × 106 t, or 0.43% of the total nitrogen reserve. In the case of global warming, eutrophic and mesotrophic bogs can become an important source of ammonia emission to the atmosphere.",,,,,,,,"Aleksandrova, L.N., Naidenova, O.A., Composition and Nature of Soil Humus Compounds (1970) Zap. Leningr. S-Kh. Inst., 142, pp. 83-156; Bambalov, N.N., (1984) Balans Organicheskogo Veshchestva Torfyanykh Pochv i Melody Ego Izucheniya (Organic Matter Budget of Peat Soils and Methods of Its Study), , Minsk: Nauka i Tekhnika; Bambalov, N.N., The Composition of Nonhydrolyzable Residue in 